pen book in my lap, smiling tenderly at the interrupted line. The call, it turned out, was for me. I sat down in a crackling wicker armchair and put the receiver to my ear. My pupils stood by, one on my right, the other on my left, imperturbably watching me.

“I’m on my way over,” said a male voice. “You will be home, I trust?”

“Your trust shall not be betrayed,” I answered cheerfully. “But who are you?”

